04473nam a22006135i 9781554580866DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102008xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545808667 a10.51644/97815545808662doi  a(DE-B1597)667741  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aN72.M6 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a7001 aElder, R. Bruce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHarmony and Dissent :bFilm and Avant-garde Art Movements in the Early Twentieth Century /cR. Bruce Elder. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2010] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (540 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Media Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- tModernism and the Absolute Film -- tThe Philosophical and Occult Background to the Absolute Film -- tModernism and the Absolute Film -- tModernism and Revolution -- tSpiritual Interests in Late Nineteenth-Century and Early Twentieth-Century Russia -- tSymbolism and its Legacies -- tConstructivism between Productivism and Suprematism -- tEisenstein, Constructivism, and the Dialectic -- tPostscript -- tConcluding Unscientific Postscript -- tAppendix -- tViking Eggeling’s Diagonal-Symphonie -- tIndex -- tFilm studies is the critical exploration of cinematic texts as art and entertainment0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aR. Bruce Elder argues that the authors of many of the manifestoes that announced in such lively ways the appearance of yet another artistic movement shared a common aspiration: they proposed to reformulate the visual, literary, and performing arts so that they might take on attributes of the cinema. The cinema, Elder argues, became, in the early decades of the twentieth century, a pivotal artistic force around which a remarkable variety and number of aesthetic forms took shape. To demonstrate this, Elder begins with a wide-ranging discussion that opens up some broad topics concerning modernity’s cognitive (and perceptual) regime, with a view to establishing that a crisis within that regime engendered some peculiar, and highly questionable, epistemological beliefs and enthusiasms. Through this discussion, Elder advances the startling claim that a crisis of cognition precipitated by modernity engendered, by way of response, a peculiar sort of “pneumatic (spiritual) epistemology.” Elder then shows that early ideas of the cinema were strongly influenced by this pneumatic epistemology and uses this conception of the cinema to explain its pivotal role in shaping two key moments in early-twentieth-century art: the quest to bring forth a pure, “objectless” (non-representational) art and Russian Suprematism, Constructivism, and Productivism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and motion pictures. 0aArt et cinéma. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics). 0aAvant-garde (Esthétique). 0aModernism (Art). 0aModernisme (Art). 0aMotion pictures and the arts. 4aArt. 4aFilm & Media. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458086640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554580866423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554580866/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles